+-------------------------------------------------------------+
|              malloc() vs calloc() vs new (C / C++)          |
+----------------------+---------------------+---------------------+------------------------------------------------+
| Feature              | malloc()            | calloc()            | new                                            |
+----------------------+---------------------+---------------------+------------------------------------------------+
| Language             | C function          | C function          | C++ operator / keyword                         |
| Purpose              | Allocates raw memory| Allocates + zeroes  | Allocates + creates object                     |
| Initialization       | Garbage values      | All bytes set to 0  | Constructor called (can init)                  |
| Type Safety          | Not type-safe       | Not type-safe       | Type-safe (returns correct type)               |
| Constructor/Destructor| Not called         | Not called          | Automatically called                           |
| Example Syntax       | int* p=(int*)malloc |int* p=(int*)calloc  |  int* p=new int[5];                            |
|                      |    (5*sizeof(int)); | (5,sizeof(int));    |                                                |
| Error Handling       | Returns NULL if fail| Returns NULL if fail| Throws bad_alloc exception                     |
| Memory Release       | free(p);            | free(p);            | delete p; or delete[] p;                       |
| Overloading          | Cannot overload     | Cannot overload     | Can overload (custom new/delete)               |
| Speed                | Slightly faster (no init) | Slightly slower (zero init) | Similar (depends on class)       |
| Simplicity in C++    | Needs type casting  | Needs type casting  | Easiest and safest in C++                      |
+----------------------+---------------------+---------------------+------------------------------------------------+

# ðŸ’¡ Quick Summary:
# malloc() â†’ Allocates raw memory only.
# calloc() â†’ Allocates + initializes memory to zero.
# new      â†’ Allocates + calls constructor (best in C++).


âœ… **In short:**  
- `malloc` â†’ Just gives you empty memory (C style).  
- `new` â†’ Gives memory **and** builds the object properly (C++ style).  
Hence, in C++, always prefer **`new`** over **`malloc`**.
